title: British journalist corrects framing of Israeli war at Columbia University
description:
British journalist Mona Chalabi corrected the framing of the Israel-Gaza war to the Israel-Palestine war when she received a Pulitzer Prize at Columbia University. In solidarity with the students of New York University facing suspension and arrest for supporting Palestine, she posted a video recorded in October 2023.
In her brief speech, Chalabi emphasised the reluctance of many attending the ceremony to address the Palestine issue. She noted that although she wasn't scheduled to give a speech, she found it necessary due to factual inaccuracies.
The British data journalist, illustrator, and writer of Iraqi descent received the prize for Illustrated Reporting and Commentary from Columbia University President Emeritus Lee Bollinger last October.
On 19 April 2024, she mentioned that she had emailed the President of Columbia in March but had not received a response.
In sharing the video, Chalabi extended her support to student protesters at Columbia University in New York, who organised the Gaza Solidarity Encampment. Over 100 pro-Palestinian protesters were arrested following its organisation. Several students at Columbia University have also been suspended from the university and its affiliated institutions.
It's noteworthy that Chalabi won the Prize for her striking illustrations, which blend statistical reporting with insightful analysis. These illustrations provide readers with a deeper understanding of Amazon founder Jeff Bezos's vast wealth and economic influence.

description:
WATCH: Hamas Chief Yahya Sinwar in Gaza Tunnel Hours Before Oct 7 Attack | Subscribe to Firstpost

Israel has released a new video of slain Hamas chief Yahya Sinwar. According to the Israeli military, the video showed Sinwar walking with his family in a tunnel under his house in Khan Younis, Gaza. The video purportedly showed Sinwar going into hiding, hours before Hamas' October 7 attack on Israel. He can be seen carrying essential supplies and a screen into the tunnel. Israel calls Sinwar the mastermind of the October 7 2023 Hamas attack, which led to a war in Gaza. The Israeli military confirmed Sinwar‚Äôs death on October 17. The Israeli military also released a video of its strike hitting a building housing Sinwar. Earlier, Israel released a video showing the final moments of Sinwar. Watch our video for more.

title: Gaza, explained
description:
Why Palestinians in Gaza have suffered for decades.

Subscribe to our channel and turn on notifications (üîî) so you don't miss any videos: http://goo.gl/0bsAjO

On October 7, Hamas, a militant group based in the Gaza Strip, launched a deadly attack on Israel, killing over 1,400 Israelis and kidnapping over 200. In retaliation, Israeli airstrikes have killed, as of this video, over 6,400 Palestinians in Gaza, where Palestinians have lived for decades under an occupation and blockade. 

Since 1967, Israel has imposed tight restrictions on travel and essential goods such as food, fuel, medicine, and water in its occupied territories. In 2007, those restrictions became even tighter in Gaza after Hamas seized power there. Since then, it has been nearly impossible for Palestinians to leave Gaza or to access an adequate supply of essential goods.

Today, the Gaza Strip, with a population of over 2 million Palestinians, is a victim of what many call ‚Äúcollective punishment‚Äù as Israel bombards its population, shuts off access to internet, power, food, water, and medicine, forces them to leave their homes, and prepares for a ground invasion.

This latest episode of Vox Atlas explains how the experience of Palestinians in Gaza got to this point, and what‚Äôs behind Israel‚Äôs occupation and its blockade of Gaza. 

Sources and readings: 

Thank you for watching! We know we couldn‚Äôt cover everything about the Gaza Strip, this was just a start. Below are a couple of sources and readings you might find helpful to learn more. 

Gisha, an Israeli nonprofit that works to protect freedom of movement for Palestinians, has done so much research on the closure of Gaza and how it impacts Palestinians there. Below are the reports and visuals that we found most useful. 
https://features.gisha.org/gaza-up-close/
https://gisha.org/en/red-lines-presentation-new-details-about-the-old-policy-while-the-current-policy-remains-shrouded-in-secrecy/
https://gisha.org/UserFiles/File/publications/separating-land-separating-people/separating-land-separating-people-web-en.pdf
https://www.gisha.org/UserFiles/File/publications/Map2020/English2020.pdf

Visualizing Palestine, a nonprofit that uses data and research to make visuals, and B‚ÄôTselem, an Israeli human rights organization, have useful databases that track fatalities over time in the Gaza Strip, Israel, and the West Bank. 
https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1VgCaY3l3jJrp0SQ3eKZ_86dfHvpSA4naYTP5RSvFJzk/edit#gid=0 
https://statistics.btselem.org/en/intro/fatalities 

This United Nations‚Äô document database helped us understand infrastructural destruction in past conflicts with Israel.
https://www.un.org/unispal/documents/ 

The Biggest Prison on Earth: A History of the Occupied Territories by Ilan Papp√©, professor of history at University of Exeter:
https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2856775-the-biggest-prison-on-earth 

The Hundred Years' War on Palestine: A History of Settler Colonialism and Resistance, 1917‚Äì2017 by Rashid Khalidi, professor of modern Arab studies at Columbia University:
https://us.macmillan.com/books/9781627798556/thehundredyearswaronpalestine
The Gaza Strip: The Political Economy of De-development by Sara Roy, senior research scholar at the Center for Middle Eastern Studies at Harvard University:
https://www.palestine-studies.org/en/node/1649448#:~:text=In%20the%20new%20expanded%20edition,known%20as%20Operation%20Protective%20Edge.

title: Armed settlers and segregation: Inside the West Bank
description:
Mohammed Robin left his home one morning to go to work, and when he came back he found it had been taken over by Israeli settlers. 
 
The property, near the West Bank City of Ramallah, had been in his family since 1952. 
 
‚ÄòI have to go the legal route to defend my land, but even with a legal process‚Ä¶ there‚Äôs not much chance,‚Äô he says. 
 
Settler encroachment is one of the most important issues in the West Bank at the moment, and it‚Äôs worsened since the October 7, 2023 Hamas attack on Israel, and the subsequent war in Gaza. 
 
Sky‚Äôs Stuart Ramsay went inside the West Bank and spoke to the Israeli military, armed settlers and the Palestinians being forced from their homes.

title: Palestinians in Gaza Hold Funeral for Hamas Political Official | VOA News
description:
Palestinians in the Gaza strip held mass funerals for two members of Hamas' political office, Jawad Abu Shammala and Zakaria Abu Maamar, killed in an airstrike in Khan Younis in southern Gaza on Tuesday, October 10. The Israeli military said they had been struck overnight. ‚Å†
‚Å†
They were the first senior Hamas members killed since Israel began pounding the enclave. Israel said Abu Shammala had led a number of operations targeting Israeli civilians. He was a member of the Hamas politburo in charge of economic affairs. ‚Å†
‚Å†
Three Gaza journalists were also killed while reporting outside a building in Gaza, bringing the number of journalists killed so far to six. ‚Å†
‚Å†
The Palestinian Foreign Ministry said Israeli strikes had since Saturday destroyed more than 22,600 residential units and 10 health facilities and damaged 48 schools. ‚Å†#Gaza #Israel #reels #videography #voanews #news #palestine

title: Palestinians in Gaza Hold Funeral for Hamas Political Official | VOA News
description:
Palestinians in the Gaza strip held mass funerals for two members of Hamas' political office, Jawad Abu Shammala and Zakaria Abu Maamar, killed in an airstrike in Khan Younis in southern Gaza on Tuesday, October 10. The Israeli military said they had been struck overnight. ‚Å†
‚Å†
They were the first senior Hamas members killed since Israel began pounding the enclave. Israel said Abu Shammala had led a number of operations targeting Israeli civilians. He was a member of the Hamas politburo in charge of economic affairs. ‚Å†
‚Å†
Three Gaza journalists were also killed while reporting outside a building in Gaza, bringing the number of journalists killed so far to six. ‚Å†
‚Å†
The Palestinian Foreign Ministry said Israeli strikes had since Saturday destroyed more than 22,600 residential units and 10 health facilities and damaged 48 schools. ‚Å†#Gaza #Israel #reels #videography #voanews #news #palestine

title: Humanitarian aid parachuted into Gaza
description:
Eyewitness footage shows humanitarian aid fell into the sea by parachutes in Gaza, on Monday March 4, 2024. There is no information about who airdropped the aid.

US military used C-130 cargo planes air-dropped its first food and aid into the Gaza Strip on Saturday March 2, 2024. The joint operation by the US Air Force and the Royal Jordanian Air Force saw US C-130 aircraft dropping 38,000 meals along the Gaza coastline, CENTCOM said in a statement.

There were 66 total bundles dropped, 22 from each of three aircraft. There was no water or medical supplies in the bundles.

title: Gaza, explained
description:
Why Palestinians in Gaza have suffered for decades.

Subscribe to our channel and turn on notifications (üîî) so you don't miss any videos: http://goo.gl/0bsAjO

On October 7, Hamas, a militant group based in the Gaza Strip, launched a deadly attack on Israel, killing over 1,400 Israelis and kidnapping over 200. In retaliation, Israeli airstrikes have killed, as of this video, over 6,400 Palestinians in Gaza, where Palestinians have lived for decades under an occupation and blockade. 

Since 1967, Israel has imposed tight restrictions on travel and essential goods such as food, fuel, medicine, and water in its occupied territories. In 2007, those restrictions became even tighter in Gaza after Hamas seized power there. Since then, it has been nearly impossible for Palestinians to leave Gaza or to access an adequate supply of essential goods.

Today, the Gaza Strip, with a population of over 2 million Palestinians, is a victim of what many call ‚Äúcollective punishment‚Äù as Israel bombards its population, shuts off access to internet, power, food, water, and medicine, forces them to leave their homes, and prepares for a ground invasion.

This latest episode of Vox Atlas explains how the experience of Palestinians in Gaza got to this point, and what‚Äôs behind Israel‚Äôs occupation and its blockade of Gaza. 

Sources and readings: 

Thank you for watching! We know we couldn‚Äôt cover everything about the Gaza Strip, this was just a start. Below are a couple of sources and readings you might find helpful to learn more. 

Gisha, an Israeli nonprofit that works to protect freedom of movement for Palestinians, has done so much research on the closure of Gaza and how it impacts Palestinians there. Below are the reports and visuals that we found most useful. 
https://features.gisha.org/gaza-up-close/
https://gisha.org/en/red-lines-presentation-new-details-about-the-old-policy-while-the-current-policy-remains-shrouded-in-secrecy/
https://gisha.org/UserFiles/File/publications/separating-land-separating-people/separating-land-separating-people-web-en.pdf
https://www.gisha.org/UserFiles/File/publications/Map2020/English2020.pdf

Visualizing Palestine, a nonprofit that uses data and research to make visuals, and B‚ÄôTselem, an Israeli human rights organization, have useful databases that track fatalities over time in the Gaza Strip, Israel, and the West Bank. 
https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1VgCaY3l3jJrp0SQ3eKZ_86dfHvpSA4naYTP5RSvFJzk/edit#gid=0 
https://statistics.btselem.org/en/intro/fatalities 

This United Nations‚Äô document database helped us understand infrastructural destruction in past conflicts with Israel.
https://www.un.org/unispal/documents/ 

The Biggest Prison on Earth: A History of the Occupied Territories by Ilan Papp√©, professor of history at University of Exeter:
https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2856775-the-biggest-prison-on-earth 

The Hundred Years' War on Palestine: A History of Settler Colonialism and Resistance, 1917‚Äì2017 by Rashid Khalidi, professor of modern Arab studies at Columbia University:
https://us.macmillan.com/books/9781627798556/thehundredyearswaronpalestine
The Gaza Strip: The Political Economy of De-development by Sara Roy, senior research scholar at the Center for Middle Eastern Studies at Harvard University:
https://www.palestine-studies.org/en/node/1649448#:~:text=In%20the%20new%20expanded%20edition,known%20as%20Operation%20Protective%20Edge.

History, genocide and Israel‚Äôs war on Gaza: Mehdi Hasan & Benny Morris | Head to Head
description:
In this episode of Head to Head, Mehdi Hasan challenges prominent Israeli historian Benny Morris on his support for Israel‚Äôs war on Gaza, the history around the founding of Israel and the Nakba.

Morris‚Äô book ‚ÄòThe Birth of the Palestinian Refugee Problem, 1947-1949‚Äô dismantled many of the myths behind the displacement of more than 700,000 Palestinians during that period. His critics, however, say he now justifies many of those crimes.

Hasan and Morris are joined by a panel of three experts:

Diana Buttu ‚Äì a Palestinian lawyer and former advisor for the PLO
Daniel Levy ‚Äì a former Israeli peace negotiator and current President of the US/ Middle East Project
Emmanuel Navon ‚Äì an International Relations lecturer at Tel Aviv University

This was filmed before the assassination of Hamas political leader Ismail Haniyeh in Iran on 31 July.

title: WATCH: Hamas Chief Yahya Sinwar in Gaza Tunnel Hours Before Oct 7 Attack | Subscribe to Firstpost
description:
WATCH: Hamas Chief Yahya Sinwar in Gaza Tunnel Hours Before Oct 7 Attack | Subscribe to Firstpost

Israel has released a new video of slain Hamas chief Yahya Sinwar. According to the Israeli military, the video showed Sinwar walking with his family in a tunnel under his house in Khan Younis, Gaza. The video purportedly showed Sinwar going into hiding, hours before Hamas' October 7 attack on Israel. He can be seen carrying essential supplies and a screen into the tunnel. Israel calls Sinwar the mastermind of the October 7 2023 Hamas attack, which led to a war in Gaza. The Israeli military confirmed Sinwar‚Äôs death on October 17. SERAMBINEWS.COM - Pasukan Pertahana Israel (IDF) di Poros Rafah Timur dihantam roket 107 mm dan mortir kaliber besar oleh Brigade Martir Al-Aqsa.

Brigade Al-Aqsa ini melesatkan roket mereka dengan bantuan peralatan super sederhana.

title: How Israel Strikes Qatar against Hamas In Doha?
description:
The Israeli assassination attempt on Palestinian negotiators in Doha targeted a residential building in the Katara District, where senior Palestinian politburo members were reportedly meeting.

We‚Äôve identified and modeled the exact building that was hit.
If you look here, you‚Äôll see five buildings lined up, with a petrol station right next door.

The Strike was was aimed at Exactly the This Building Without damaging the Other Four including the Petrol Station

The strike was a success and carried out against the one in the middle, using a precision-guided weapons around 10 in Numbers to be precise all launched at the Same time.
possibly an American made G P S guidance J dam, a Spike Laser Guided Bomb, or even a Rampage missile all used in Multiple combinations.
But the real question is‚Äîhow did Israel know exactly which building to strike?
Since the start of the Gaza war on October 7, the Qatar Amiri Guard has been stationed around that structure 24 hours a day.
That heavy security presence was a giveaway.

The building, located next to the petrol station in Doha‚Äôs Katara District, has been used to host high-profile Palestinian leaders.

The Amiri Guard‚Äôs mission is to protect these key political figures and shield them from external threats‚Äîpart of Qatar‚Äôs careful balancing act of hosting Hamas leadership while safeguarding its own security and diplomatic position in the region.

So how did the Israelis manage to penetrate this protective ring?
According to intelligence assessments, Israel‚Äôs internal security agency, Shin Bet, tracked the Palestinian officials in Doha using a layered mix of intelligence techniques.
These likely included human sources on the ground, signals intelligence through intercepted communications, aerial or satellite surveillance, and possibly advanced cyber tools.
Cross-checking these inputs allowed Israel to pinpoint the exact building and confirm the timing of the Palestinian leadership meeting.
This set the stage for a precision strike designed to minimize civilian losses while focusing on senior Palestinian targets.
The operation also highlights how difficult such a mission is from a purely technical standpoint.
The flight distance from Israel to Doha is roughly 1200 miles this is around 2,000 kilometers one way‚Äîwell beyond the combat radius of fully armed Israeli fighter jets.
That means mid-air refueling wasn‚Äôt just helpful, it was essential.
About 15 Israeli fighters are believed to have been involved in the strike mission, flying more than a thousand miles each way.
To pull this off, the aircraft had to link up with Boeing 7 "O' 7-based aerial tankers mid-flight.
These airborne refueling platforms gave the strike package the extra range and loiter time needed to reach Doha, conduct the operation, and return safely.
Both the outbound and return legs required discreet refueling, most likely carried out over international or third-party airspace to avoid radar detection.

title: ‚ÄúGet the F*** Out of Gaza!‚Äù Trump Seals Israel-Hamas Peace Deal | With Cenk Uygur & Daniella Weiss
description:
President Donald Trump has announced that both Israel and Hamas have agreed to the first phase of a peace deal. Could this really be the end of the war in Gaza - and will it last?

description:

Israeli forces stopped some of the Palestinians from entering the Al-Aqsa compound in Jerusalem. The Palestinians weren‚Äôt allowed to perform Friday prayers. The blockade forced some people to pray on the streets. Israel said it may limit the worshipping at the holy site during Ramadan for security reasons. Al-Aqsa has long been a flashpoint of violence.

description:
CCTV shows how two Hamas fighters broke into a kibbutz community.

Shortly after a resident's vehicle arrived at the gate and the pair ambushed the driver, killing all the passengers.

title: British journalist corrects framing of Israeli war at Columbia University
description:
British journalist Mona Chalabi corrected the framing of the Israel-Gaza war to the Israel-Palestine war when she received a Pulitzer Prize at Columbia University. In solidarity with the students of New York University facing suspension and arrest for supporting Palestine, she posted a video recorded in October 2023.
In her brief speech, Chalabi emphasised the reluctance of many attending the ceremony to address the Palestine issue. She noted that although she wasn't scheduled to give a speech, she found it necessary due to factual inaccuracies.
The British data journalist, illustrator, and writer of Iraqi descent received the prize for Illustrated Reporting and Commentary from Columbia University President Emeritus Lee Bollinger last October.
On 19 April 2024, she mentioned that she had emailed the President of Columbia in March but had not received a response.
In sharing the video, Chalabi extended her support to student protesters at Columbia University in New York, who organised the Gaza Solidarity Encampment. Over 100 pro-Palestinian protesters were arrested following its organisation. Several students at Columbia University have also been suspended from the university and its affiliated institutions.
It's noteworthy that Chalabi won the Prize for her striking illustrations, which blend statistical reporting with insightful analysis. These illustrations provide readers with a deeper understanding of Amazon founder Jeff Bezos's vast wealth and economic influence.

title: History, genocide and Israel‚Äôs war on Gaza: Mehdi Hasan & Benny Morris | Head to Head
description:
In this episode of Head to Head, Mehdi Hasan challenges prominent Israeli historian Benny Morris on his support for Israel‚Äôs war on Gaza, the history around the founding of Israel and the Nakba.

Morris‚Äô book ‚ÄòThe Birth of the Palestinian Refugee Problem, 1947-1949‚Äô dismantled many of the myths behind the displacement of more than 700,000 Palestinians during that period. His critics, however, say he now justifies many of those crimes.

Hasan and Morris are joined by a panel of three experts:

Diana Buttu ‚Äì a Palestinian lawyer and former advisor for the PLO
Daniel Levy ‚Äì a former Israeli peace negotiator and current President of the US/ Middle East Project
Emmanuel Navon ‚Äì an International Relations lecturer at Tel Aviv University

This was filmed before the assassination of Hamas political leader Ismail Haniyeh in Iran on 31 July.

title: ‚ÄòGod gave us Israel, all of it‚Äô | Along the Green Line: episode 1
description:
Since the war in Gaza and the expanding occupation of the West Bank, a peaceful resolution to the conflict between Israelis and Palestinians feels more distant than ever.
Subscribe to The Guardian on YouTube ‚ñ∫ http://bit.ly/subscribegdn

In this three-part series, the reporter Matthew Cassel travels along the 1949 Armistice border, or ‚ÄòGreen Line‚Äô, once seen as the best hope for a resolution. He meets Palestinians and Israelis living just kilometres apart, but shaped by vastly different realities. This first episode begins in East Jerusalem, a city at the heart of the conflict

Chapters:
00:00 - What is the green line? The Gaza war and the two state solution
01:54 - Do you know what the green line is? 
02:30 - The erasure of the green line
04:40 - Making all of Jerusalem Jewish
06:35 - Destroying the Al-aqsa mosque to build the third temple. 
09:50 - The only homeland for Palestinians
11:05 - The silencing and imprisonment of Palestinians
13:18 - Palestinians feel fear living in Jerusalem
14:42 - An Israeli settler-led tour arrives on the scene

title: Palestinians in Gaza Hold Funeral for Hamas Political Official | VOA News
description:
Palestinians in the Gaza strip held mass funerals for two members of Hamas' political office, Jawad Abu Shammala and Zakaria Abu Maamar, killed in an airstrike in Khan Younis in southern Gaza on Tuesday, October 10. The Israeli military said they had been struck overnight. ‚Å†
‚Å†
